| Mixed | 0.16 | 0.51 | 1.33 | 2.57x |

--- Arithmetic Intensity Analysis ---
Arithmetic Intensity = FLOPs / Memory Bytes
Memory bound: AI < 1.0 FLOP/byte
Compute bound: AI > 1.0 FLOP/byte
Add: 0.26 GFLOPS, AI = 0.005 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)
Mul: 0.25 GFLOPS, AI = 0.005 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)
FMA: 0.49 GFLOPS, AI = 0.010 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)
Div: 0.29 GFLOPS, AI = 0.006 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)
Sqrt: 0.21 GFLOPS, AI = 0.004 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)
Trig: 0.25 GFLOPS, AI = 0.005 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)
Mixed: 0.67 GFLOPS, AI = 0.013 FLOP/byte
  -> Memory bound (AI < 1.0)

--- Key Insights ---
1. FMA is most efficient: single instruction for multiply+add
2. Division and sqrt are 10-100x slower than add/mul
3. Trigonometry is very expensive - avoid in tight loops
4. Arithmetic Intensity determines if kernel is memory or compute bound
5. Optimize instruction mix before memory access patterns

